  <h2>Homesteading: A Thriver's Guide</h2>
  <p class="auth">Posted by kev
  <span class="typo_date" title="Sat, 24 Jun 2006 23:36:00 GMT">Sat, 24 Jun 2006 23:36:00 GMT</span></p>
  <div id="adsense">
  <script type="text/javascript"><!--
google_ad_client = "pub-1730274975094059";
google_ad_width = 468;
google_ad_height = 60;
google_ad_format = "468x60_as";
google_ad_type = "text";
google_ad_channel ="";
google_color_border = "FFFFFF";
google_color_bg = "FFFFFF";
google_color_link = "5189B5";
google_color_url = "000000";
google_color_text = "000000";
//--></script>
<script type="text/javascript"
  src="http://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/show_ads.js">
</script>
  </div>
  <p>Tonight after Mike Clark&#8217;s talk, Nathaniel Talbott gave an excellent follow up to his RubyConf 2005 talk, &#8221;<a href="http://glu.ttono.us/articles/2005/10/16/rails-serving-the-long-tail-in-1883-and-2005">Serving the Long Tail in 1883 and 2005</a>&#8221; to the full conference. Read past the jump for more.</p><p>RubyConf 2005 - The Longtail of Software</p>

<ul>
<li>The railroad in the 19th century opened up the frontier</li>
<li>Rails has done similar things for the web</li>
<li>One of the points was Homesteading vs Goldrushing
<ul>
<li>Weak because it was really a talk of its own.</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>

<p>Talk in 10 Acts</p>

<p>Act 1: Train</p>

<ul>
<li>1870 Boston. Bobby is a shop keeper. 
<ul>
<li>Well, he&#8217;s a shop manager. He knows the ins and outs of keeping the shop but he doesn&#8217;t own it.</li>
<li>Bobby is starting to hear things about the frontier and is getting interested in going to get his own place and land which he can&#8217;t do in Boston.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>The homesteading act has been passed.
<ul>
<li>If you go out, you can stake out land. If you live on it for four years and have a house on it, it&#8217;s yours free and clear. Land is also available cheap.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>What is homesteading for the 21st century?
<ul>
<li>Building small, stable businesses we own.</li>
<li>Firewheel design with iconbuffet, 37 signals, Pragmatic Bookshelf</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Why homestead?
<ul>
<li>Opportunity cost
<ul>
<li>The value of the next best thing you could be doing</li>
<li>If you&#8217;re employed, what you could get paid if you become a contractor</li>
<li>There are also non monetary op costs</li>
<li>What could you be learning if you aren&#8217;t doing what you&#8217;re doing?</li>
<li>How are you being marketed by what you&#8217;re doing?</li>
<li>Life as risk management.</li>
<li>&#8220;So teach us to number our days, that we may apply our hearts unto wisdom.&#8221;</li>
<li>We can only choose what to do now, but it effects our options.</li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
<li>So Bobby says, &#8220;Should I go on the train and go out west?&#8221;</li>
<li>Buying the ticket means you&#8217;re going to leave. And you&#8217;re at risk.</li>
</ul>

<p>Act 2: Land</p>

<ul>
<li>HowTo</li>
<li>Bobby buys a ticket and wants to go West.
<ul>
<li>&#8220;Where do I stop along the way?&#8221;</li>
<li>He does research.</li>
<li>&#8220;Where do I <em>want</em> to be and see? What interests me?&#8221;</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Land is where you stake out your space.</li>
<li>&#8220;Prepare your outside work, make it fit for yourself in the field, and afterward build your house.&#8221;</li>
<li>How can you take your skills and do what you love?</li>
<li>I wanted to make my living doing service based work.
<ul>
<li>Jumping into consulting I could learn business and learn skills to get where I wanted to be.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Our land is <strong>limitless</strong> and there&#8217;s room for everyone</li>
<li>Bobby finds a place off the rail and makes a shop in the mountains.</li>
</ul>

<p>Act 3: Sunrise</p>

<ul>
<li>We need to keep moving.</li>
<li>&#8220;A little sleep, a little slumber, a little folding of the hands to sleep &#8211; so shall your poverty come on you like a prowler and your need like an armed man&#8221;</li>
<li>Getting Things Done helps me with time management
<ul>
<li>43 folders</li>
<li>Printable CEO</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>

<p>Act 4: Community</p>

<ul>
<li>If you&#8217;re by yourself you&#8217;re in trouble.</li>
<li>Bobby needs a community around him. He can run a shop, but doesn&#8217;t know how to run a farm.</li>
<li>&#8220;Though one may be overpowered by another, two can withstand him. And a threefold cord is not quickly broken.&#8221;</li>
<li>Family is an integral part of the Homestead.
<ul>
<li>Just because getting family involved can cause problems doesn&#8217;t mean you shouldn&#8217;t do it.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>If you take care of your family, they will take care of you</li>
<li>Neighbors
<ul>
<li>Sharing helps everyone</li>
<li>Mashups are generated by people working together</li>
<li>Competitors can help!</li>
<li>Good fences make good neighbors
<ul>
<li>Set expectations</li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
<li>Town
<ul>
<li>You need a place you can work with others apart from direct neighbors</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>

<p>Act 5: Tools</p>

<ul>
<li>Plowing a field is hard without a horse or an ox
<ul>
<li>&#8220;When no oxen are, the trough is clean; but much increase comes by the strength of an ox.&#8221;</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Tools are a multiplier.
<ul>
<li>They&#8217;re worth paying for when useful.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Marketing is sales automation</li>
<li>It isn&#8217;t a complete solution
<ul>
<li>You&#8217;ll still need to do some things</li>
<li>Do what you do best</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>

<p>Act 6: Sunday</p>

<ul>
<li>Bobby is going to be working hard, but on Sunday he&#8217;ll do something different. His day of rest.</li>
<li>We need rest and change of pace or we&#8217;re no longer productive.</li>
<li>What&#8217;s the point if we don&#8217;t enjoy it?
<ul>
<li>&#8220;For all his days are sorrowful, and his work burdensome; even in the night his heart takes no rest. This also is vanity.&#8221;</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Take time for yourself regularly.</li>
<li>Resting isn&#8217;t always vacation. Maybe you just do something different.</li>
<li>You don&#8217;t have time not to take time. It costs your more not to do it.</li>
</ul>

<p>Act 7: Inheritance</p>

<ul>
<li>What&#8217;s the value of what Bobby is doing?
<ul>
<li>He&#8217;s crafting this untamed wilderness into something his future family can use. </li>
<li>He&#8217;s building wealth out of nothing.</li>
<li>&#8220;A good man leaves an inheritance to his children&#8217;s children&#8221;</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Wealth is not a zero sum game and not always monetary.</li>
<li>It isn&#8217;t about things. It&#8217;s about the non material things.</li>
<li>In homesteading, I want to pass skills on to my children that they can use as they grow older.</li>
</ul>

<p>Act 8: Love</p>

<ul>
<li>After 5 years Bobby looks back on the last 5 years.
<ul>
<li>He&#8217;s not working in the town, he&#8217;s working on his homestead</li>
<li>The sun is rising over the mountain in the morning as he works</li>
<li>Life is good</li>
</ul></li>
<li>&#8220;Nothing is better for a man than that he should eat and drink, and that his soul should enjoy good in his labor.&#8221;</li>
<li>What are you passionate and are you doing it now?</li>
<li>Sometimes you have to do things you don&#8217;t love&#8230;
<ul>
<li>But they allow us to do the things we do love</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Never lose your love for people.</li>
<li>Never lose your love for learning and improving.
<ul>
<li>Don&#8217;t give in to the 9 to 5</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>

<p>Act 9: Weather</p>

<ul>
<li>It starts to rain and it looks to be a pretty bad storm.</li>
<li>Some things happen that you can&#8217;t predict or control.
<ul>
<li>They&#8217;re your best friend and your worst enemy</li>
<li>They can provide opportunities or destroy you</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Be careful of assumptions.</li>
<li>&#8220;Like fish taken in a cruel net, like birds caught in a snare, so the sons of men are snared in an evil time&#8230;&#8221;</li>
<li>The bubble hurt, but homesteading skills are useful all the time</li>
<li>Debt is a killer here.</li>
</ul>

<p>Act 10: Death</p>

<ul>
<li>How is Bobby&#8217;s tombstone going to be different now than it had been in Boston?</li>
<li>&#8220;To everything there is a season, a time for every purpose under heaven: A time to be born, and a time to die&#8230;&#8221;</li>
<li>Consider the exit plan.</li>
<li>When will you be done with this?
<ul>
<li>Don&#8217;t become a corporate zombie.</li>
<li>Maybe you get bought out. Maybe something better comes alone.</li>
<li>What&#8217;s the end goal?</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Think about how you define success?
<ul>
<li>Thinking about the job, family, life, what defines success?</li>
</ul></li>
<li>If you thought you would die tomorrow (or in two weeks), would you be doing the same thing today?</li>
</ul>

<p>Buy the Ticket!</p>

<ul>
<li>I want you to leave reconsidering your situation.</li>
<li>You are at risk, measure the risk, ferret out the assumptions you&#8217;re making and make sure that all you do is getting consideration.</li>
<li>The opportunity is amazing.</li>
<li><strong>Buy the Ticket!</strong></li>
</ul>

<p>Barnraising</p>

<ul>
<li>I&#8217;ve got a cool idea, I&#8217;ve got the land staked off but I need to raise the first building.
<ul>
<li>Find others with similar ideas.</li>
<li>Prep things.</li>
<li>Focus on helping one of the communities raising their barn.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Look at Rails day. We can do this.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<p class="meta">
  
</p>



